  {
    "title": "During the interim government\u2019s tenure, the Chittagong Port became a coveted pla...",
    "description": "During the interim government\u2019s tenure, the Chittagong Port became a coveted place for deal-making. We all know how the Laldia Container Terminal deal was handed over to APM Terminals and a local company QNS Container Services under a veil of secrecy. To date, we are none the wiser about the terms and conditions of that deal, which is unusual for PPP deals in this day and age. It has now emerged that another container terminal is being built near the Laldia Container Terminal that was not in the Chittagong Port Authority\u2019s plan. And that terminal was awarded to the local company Transmarine Logistics, a concern of MGH Group, in an underhanded manner and with generous benefits. Were that valuable parcel of land leased out following the due process, the government would have gotten a far higher amount. The lessee was given two years grace period on rent, depriving the state of Tk 46 crore. Because of this particular deal, the government will lose out on hundreds of crores of taka. When a few local media wanted to do a report on this, the chief adviser\u2019s press wing intimidated them. But Jago News did the report eventually. The MGH Group, it seems, was a major beneficiary of the interim government. The MGH Group CEO Anis Ahmed\u2019s legal cases were all cleared. He has gotten this valuable land to build the country\u2019s first private container terminal without following proper tender process and by violating rules. He might have also gotten the permit to launch an airline, Fly Falcon. He also got media licence. Who are the editor and executive editor of his media project, The Daily Waadaa? Shafiqul Alam and Azad Majumder, the press secretary and deputy press secretary of the chief adviser respectively, who became MGH employees the day after the interim government\u2019s tenure ended. Last but not the least, the port deal at least couldn\u2019t have been done without the blessing of Ashik of Chowdhury, who is the executive chairman of Bangladesh Investment Development Authority (BIDA) and chief executive officer of the Public Private Partnership Authority (PPPA).",
